## 4. Registry Strategies — Wiring Validation into the API Server

**`kubernetes--v1.32.0` → `pkg/registry/core/secret/strategy.go`**

```go
// line 88–90
func (strategy) ValidateUpdate(ctx context.Context, obj, old runtime.Object) field.ErrorList {
    return validation.ValidateSecretUpdate(obj.(*api.Secret), old.(*api.Secret))
}
```

**`kubernetes--v1.32.0` → `pkg/registry/core/configmap/strategy.go`**

```go
// line 84–88
func (strategy) ValidateUpdate(ctx context.Context, newObj, oldObj runtime.Object) field.ErrorList {
    oldCfg, newCfg := oldObj.(*api.ConfigMap), newObj.(*api.ConfigMap)
    return validation.ValidateConfigMapUpdate(newCfg, oldCfg)
}
```

These `strategy` types implement `rest.RESTUpdateStrategy`. The API server's generic REST machinery calls `ValidateUpdate` on every `PUT` and `PATCH` request before writing to etcd. This is the enforcement point for all API clients — `kubectl`, controllers, and the kubelet alike.

---

## 5. Kubelet Watch Optimization — Skipping Watches for Immutable Objects

This is the performance half of the feature. Once a ConfigMap or Secret is known to be immutable, the kubelet stops maintaining a live watch for it, since the data can never change.

### 5a. Type Alias and Cache Item State

**`kubernetes--v1.32.0` → `pkg/kubelet/util/manager/watch_based_manager.go`**

```go
// line 44 — the callback type injected by callers
type isImmutableFunc func(runtime.Object) bool

// lines 46–64 — the per-object cache entry
type objectCacheItem struct {
    refMap    map[types.UID]int
    store     *cacheStore
    reflector *cache.Reflector
    hasSynced func() (bool, error)
    waitGroup sync.WaitGroup

    // lock protects lastAccessTime, stopped, and immutable
    lock           sync.Mutex
    lastAccessTime time.Time
    stopped        bool
    immutable      bool   // ← set permanently once the object is seen as immutable
    stopCh         chan struct{}
}
```

### 5b. `setImmutable()` — Marking the Cache Item

```go
// lines 90–94
func (i *objectCacheItem) setImmutable() {
    i.lock.Lock()
    defer i.lock.Unlock()
    i.immutable = true
}
```

Once called, `immutable` is never cleared. It is a permanent, monotonic transition.

### 5c. `restartReflectorIfNeeded()` — The Skip Guard

```go
// lines 109–118
func (i *objectCacheItem) restartReflectorIfNeeded() {
    i.lock.Lock()
    defer i.lock.Unlock()
    if i.immutable || !i.stopped {   // ← immutable items are never restarted
        return
    }
    i.stopCh = make(chan struct{})
    i.stopped = false
    go i.startReflector()
}
```

Idle watches are periodically stopped by `startRecycleIdleWatch`. For mutable objects, `restartReflectorIfNeeded` re-establishes the watch on the next `Get`. For immutable objects, the guard at line 112 (`if i.immutable`) short-circuits this — the reflector stays stopped forever.

### 5d. `stopThreadUnsafe()` — Preserving Cache on Immutable Stop

```go
// lines 72–82
func (i *objectCacheItem) stopThreadUnsafe() bool {
    if i.stopped {
        return false
    }
    i.stopped = true
    close(i.stopCh)
    if !i.immutable {
        i.store.unsetInitialized()  // ← only clears cache for mutable objects
    }
    return true
}
```

When a mutable watch is stopped (e.g., due to idle timeout), the store is marked uninitialized so the next `Get` triggers a fresh list+watch. For immutable objects, the cached data is preserved permanently — there is no need to re-fetch.

### 5e. `Get()` — The Detection and Stop Trigger

```go
// lines 332–351
if c.isImmutable(object) {
    item.setImmutable()
    if item.stop() {
        klog.V(4).InfoS("Stopped watching for changes - object is immutable", "obj", klog.KRef(namespace, name))
    }
}
return object, nil
```

On every `Get`, after the object is retrieved from the local cache, `isImmutable` is called. The first time it returns `true`, `setImmutable()` and `stop()` are called. Subsequent calls to `Get` still return the cached value (the store is not cleared), but no watch is running. The comment in the code explains the deliberate design choice:

> *we may potentially not even start the reflector if the object is already immutable. However, given that we want to also handle the case when object is marked as immutable later … we limit ourselves to just quickly stop the reflector here.*

### 5f. `NewObjectCache` and `NewWatchBasedManager` — Constructor Signatures

```go
// lines 176–204
func NewObjectCache(
    listObject   listObjectFunc,
    watchObject  watchObjectFunc,
    newObject    newObjectFunc,
    isImmutable  isImmutableFunc,   // ← injected callback
    groupResource schema.GroupResource,
    clock        clock.Clock,
    maxIdleTime  time.Duration,
    stopCh       <-chan struct{}) Store { ... }

// lines 383–400
func NewWatchBasedManager(
    listObject          listObjectFunc,
    watchObject         watchObjectFunc,
    newObject           newObjectFunc,
    isImmutable         isImmutableFunc,   // ← injected callback
    groupResource       schema.GroupResource,
    resyncInterval      time.Duration,
    getReferencedObjects func(*v1.Pod) sets.Set[string]) Manager { ... }
```

`isImmutableFunc` is a dependency-injected strategy, keeping the generic watch manager decoupled from the specific ConfigMap/Secret types.

