  "key_design_decisions": [
    {
      "decision": "One-way immutability transition",
      "detail": "Validation checks oldObject.Immutable, not newObject.Immutable. This means mutable→immutable is always allowed on any update, but once set, immutable=true cannot be cleared. The object must be deleted and recreated to become mutable again."
    },
    {
      "decision": "Metadata changes always allowed",
      "detail": "ValidateSecretUpdate and ValidateConfigMapUpdate only freeze data/binaryData and the immutable field itself. ObjectMeta (labels, annotations, finalizers, etc.) can always be updated, even on immutable objects."
    },
    {
      "decision": "StringData not re-validated",
      "detail": "In ValidateSecretUpdate, StringData is not compared because the API server merges StringData into Data before validation runs. Comparing Data is sufficient."
    },
    {
      "decision": "Watch stopped lazily, not eagerly",
      "detail": "The kubelet does not skip starting the reflector when an object is first registered, even if it is already immutable. The watch is started normally and stopped on the first Get() that observes immutable=true. This handles the case where an object becomes immutable after initial registration without requiring reflector refactoring."
    },
    {
      "decision": "Cache preserved on immutable stop",
      "detail": "objectCacheItem.stopThreadUnsafe() calls store.unsetInitialized() only when !i.immutable. For immutable items, the cached data is preserved permanently so subsequent Gets can be served from cache without any network call."
    },
    {
      "decision": "isImmutableFunc is dependency-injected",
      "detail": "The generic watch_based_manager.go knows nothing about ConfigMap or Secret types. The type-specific check (configMap.Immutable != nil && *configMap.Immutable) is provided as a closure by configmap_manager.go and secret_manager.go, keeping the watch manager reusable for any object type."
    },
    {
      "decision": "Nil-safe three-valued bool semantics",
      "detail": "Immutable is *bool, not bool. This gives three states: nil (field absent/unset, treated as mutable), &false (explicitly mutable), &true (immutable). The closures and validation all use the pattern 'Immutable != nil && *Immutable' to correctly distinguish nil from false."
    }
  ]
